// The previous attempt asserted the implication's LHS as standalone facts
// (`assert(post1_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))` etc.),
// but those conjuncts are only the antecedent of the postcondition's
// `({...}) ==> det_set_equal(...)` implication — they are NOT available
// as proof-body facts. That's why Verus rejected lines 1547 and 1548.
//
// The lex-clean repair is to phrase each helper assertion in the
// conditional `A ==> B` form, which is universally provable from
// `requires` alone (the implication itself is a tautology: if both seqs
// are extensionally equal to the SAME `pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out)`,
// then by `axiom_seq_ext_equal` they are extensionally — and hence
// structurally — equal to each other). Each conditional `==>` assert
// adds a hypothesis-to-conclusion trigger link that z3 can chain through
// when discharging the postcondition's outer implication.
//
// We expose every projection det_set_equal might compare on:
//   * `.seq@`            – Seq<A>, the ghost view of the Seq field
//   * `.@` (i.e. view()) – `#[verifier(inline)]` = `.seq@`
// and emit each link in both `=~=` (ext-equal) and `==` (structural) form
// so the trigger fires regardless of which equality z3 latches onto.
assert((post1_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))
       && (post2_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))
       ==> post1_self_.seq@ =~= post2_self_.seq@);
assert((post1_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))
       && (post2_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))
       ==> post1_self_.seq@ == post2_self_.seq@);
assert((post1_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))
       && (post2_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))
       ==> post1_self_@ =~= post2_self_@);
assert((post1_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))
       && (post2_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out))
       ==> post1_self_@ == post2_self_@);

// `r1` and `r2` are both of type `()`, a singleton — trivially equal.
assert(r1 == r2);
